					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Having studied Computer Science for 4 years, the only assembly I saw over there was in Computer Architecture classes. It didn't help much though, I learned much more from the internet.
<br />
<br />I'm not really sure how it is with Computer Engineering, but I guess they'd focus more on the architecture of processors, which should mean looking into some assembly, but maybe they aren't as focused in programming logic.
<br />
<br />Whatever you choose, don't expect to learn how to program games in college. Every programming course nowadays (excluding those specific to games) will only focus on basic logic operations while the students are first learning how to program, and the advanced classes will be all about modern application crap: forms, databases, reports and that kind of shit. most programmers have no clue on how to make a real-time interactive program such as a game.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

